just for sharing that, i was curious today about **why the generation loop of the matrix used in cvFindExtrinsicCameraParams2**:
https://github.com/opencv/opencv/blob/4de115c08cd751d9cf3a45f593e217a104ab8fa0/modules/calib3d/src/calibration.cpp#L1184
**is different than the used in  CvHomographyEstimator::runKernel**:
https://github.com/opencv/opencv/blob/4de115c08cd751d9cf3a45f593e217a104ab8fa0/modules/calib3d/src/fundam.cpp#L162
it is the same kind of symmetric matrix as used in homography DLT, but plus 4 columns per row (as part of the math derivation);
so i write the same kind of loop used in CvHomographyEstimator::runKernel for replacing the cvFindExtrinsicCameraParams2 loop, did some tests, and i got the follow results (just doing the generation and SVD). So is just one matrix of 12x12, instead of having matMultTranspose over a matrix of Nx12 points. The results showed that is faster, after ~30 points (not optimized) and always faster if optimized, at least, in in visual c 10, OX flag, optimize for speed, full opt.
The tests.... For each set of N random points = {10 to 100} and projections, i used 500 repeated tests without stop, then averaged and compute variance for those and repeated 10 times this procedure, finally computed mean and variance over the 10. the variances seemed small, so i ignored them.
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/3331458/64477097-61a14c00-d18f-11e9-9b7e-33ebb2666599.png)
also i **tried to use the jacobi eigenvalue algorithm** as for symmetric matrices just one **UDU' decomposition** (not a UDVt?) seems necessary; but the tests revealed to be slower (i believed that would be faster than the general SVD (used in cv::SVD);  well, maybe is due that my opencv project is not compiled with optimization flags, or it is really more slower.
the code has just a test over the loop.
